article.description: The New York Liberty ended Washington's nine-game home winning streak by beating the Mystics 67-53 Saturday behind Vickie Johnson's 19 points.
article.headline: Johnson scores 19 as Liberty upend Mystics
article.linkText: Liberty hand Mystics first home loss of season
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The New York Liberty ended Washington's nine-game home winning streak by beating the Mystics 67-53 Saturday behind Vickie Johnson's 19 points.

	   The Mystics were 8-0 in Washington this season -- the WNBA's only
unbeaten home record -- and won their home finale in 2001.

	   ''It was a big win for us, to play a first-place team on their
floor and get an effort like we got,'' Liberty coach Richie Adubato
said. ''We outrebounded their people, and that was the best first
half of defense we've played this year.''

	   Tari Phillips had 13 points and a season-high 12 rebounds, and
Crystal Robinson scored 15 for New York (11-9), which extended its
winning streak over the Mystics to five games and moved within
three games of first-place Washington (14-6) in the Eastern
Conference.

	   Coco Miller and Helen Luz each had 11 points for Washington,
which played its fifth consecutive game without the injured
Chamique Holdsclaw, the team's leading scorer and rebounder.

	   ''Holdsclaw didn't play; we understand that,'' Adubato said.
''They are the most talented team in the East when they have
Holdsclaw. You put Holdsclaw in that lineup and they definitely are
the team to beat in the East.''

	   After giving the Liberty a 40-22 lead on a 3-pointer from the
corner, Robinson picked up her fourth foul with 16:43 remaining.
She finished with five rebounds and five assists.

	   Consecutive layups by Tonya Washington, who scored a season-high
nine points, pulled the Mystics to 47-34 with 13:43 remaining. Her
3-pointer pulled Washington to 49-41 with 9½ minutes left, but the
Mystics never got closer than eight points.

	   The Mystics made only three of their first 16 shots and fell
behind 13-8 in the first nine minutes.

	   ''Our intensity level today was extremely low,'' Miller said.
''We came out pretty flat, a little sluggish, and our shooting
percentage wasn't good at all. We missed a lot of early shots, and
from there, we never really played very well.''

	   Phillips had nine points and nine rebounds in the first half.
Robinson also had nine points by halftime.
